title.narrative: 003 PREVENTION OF MICRONUTRIENT DEFICIENCIES

description.narrative: By 2025, boys and girls aged 6-59 months, adolescents and pregnant/lactating women have access to micronutrient programs to prevent deficiencies, which contributes to Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition In Early Childhood (Covid), Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2025, chronic malnutrition (stunting) and wasting in children is reduced including in humanitarian situations

title.narrative: By 2025, boys and girls aged 6-59 months, adolescents and pregnant/lactating women have access to micronutrient programs to preventdeficiencies

description.narrative: Nationally, UNICEF and Government effort to provide supplements has had positive results reaching 10.75 and 7.24 million children aged 6-59 months with vitamin A supplementation respectively in both semesters. The different crises have reduced by over 2 million children the number receiving 2 doses compared to 2020. Similarly, 5.48 million children 24-59 months received two doses of deworming, and over 1.4 million pregnant women were supplemented with Iron-Folic Acid (IFA) every semester. Contrary to previous year, the northern crisis (Afar, Amhara and Tigray,) has significantly impacted the delivery of supplementation due to disruption in the delivery facilities. | Status:Partially met | As-of Date:07/01/2022
